reviewText: The first two of a trilogy of college films with Kurt Russell.Given a ten-movie contract with Disney he did an excellent job keeping several"second [Phil Silvers] banana" actors afloat until death---or Social Security---took over.I've got these two films--on two discs-- in a clear empty QUAD DVD box with t-h-ethird film: NOW YOU SEE HIM, NOW YOU DON'T....No Academy Award stuff, here, but certainly NOT "JACK & JILL" either.Recommended, harmless, mildly entertaining fluff of interest to those of us INCalifornia in the late `sixties, early `seventies... that DON'T have time-machines.

reviewText: I measure all Disney movies by the standouts of the genre, the fantastic Gus and the great Super Dad, both of which had the incomparable sex addict Bob Crane in each of them. These lame movies simply don't stack up, and I don't care if they have Kurt Russell in them or were set in California. Those aren't reasons to buy these movies. A reviewer should tell you something about the movie, not babble on incoherently about his own life (see "O's" aka Sgt McCluskey aka Mikey review below). These movies, unlike Gus and Super Dad, simply aren't believable. A computer can't wear tennis shoes and we all know that while Kurt Russell may have some strength, he is certainly not the strongest man in the world. My advice is to skip the Kurt Russell years at Disney and revel in the Bob Crane years, with the knowledge that while Gus and Super Dad were being filmed, Crane was having wild orgies every night and making nudie films. Lends more spice to the otherwise mundane Disney proceedings.
summary: Not as good as Gus and Super Dad

reviewText: Young Kurt Russell playing a college student doing all kinds of cheesy things.  You can't go wrong.  They're even kind of sci-fi but in a very un-serious way.  I remember seeing The Computer Wore Tennis Shoes when the Disney Channel would transmit on scrambled for promotional week.  It was good stuff then, and is still good now.  I recommend this set.
